description.narrative: by 2023, (social) service providers have increased capacities to provide equitable, quality and gender-sensitive services for adolescent girls and boys., which contributes to Access To Quality Learning Opportunities, Access To Quality Learning Opportunities (Covid), Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Learning, Skills, Participation And Engagement, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being, Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women, Prevention Of Harmful Practice, Promotion Of Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being And Justice, Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By the end of 2023, adolescents are learning, healthy, developing and participating in an environment free from violence, exploitation and abuse.

description.narrative: UNICEF contributed to minimizing school closures and keeping children learning face-to-face during COVID-19 through advocacy, inter-sectorial collaboration in the prevention and rapid response to the crisis. Nonetheless, the impact of the crisis since 2020 remains worrisome, with continued learning loss, high numbers of learner pregnancies and children who have not returned to school. Deaths and sickness, sexual and gender-based violence in communities has contributed to mental health issues amongst teachers and learners. Thus, the government continues to focus onrecovering learning loss, providing psychosocial support, including relief through sports, as well as child protection services to children and adolescents.; | Status:On-track | As-of Date:15/12/2021
